1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:04,060
 Now that we've talked about forms a bit, I want to talk a little bit about security in forms.

2
00:00:04,060 --> 00:00:10,940
 I want to talk about a security issue called cross-site request forgery, or CSRF.

3
00:00:10,940 --> 00:00:16,220
 So the idea of a CSRF attack is that a rogue site,

4
00:00:16,220 --> 00:00:18,720
 it has to do with cookies and how cookies get sent to sites.

5
00:00:18,720 --> 00:00:21,360
 So let's say you're logged into a MySite,

6
00:00:21,360 --> 00:00:24,960
 and a rogue site generates a page that's going to post.

7
00:00:24,960 --> 00:00:29,260
 And on every form, you can post to a site other than the one it came from.

8
00:00:29,260 --> 00:00:34,760
 And so if I can get data that I want to send to the legitimate server,

9
00:00:34,760 --> 00:00:40,440
 the rogue site can set up a post, and then if I can convince you to hit the button,

10
00:00:40,440 --> 00:00:44,700
 then it will grab the cookie and send it to the legitimate server that you're already logged into,

11
00:00:44,700 --> 00:00:46,840
 and perhaps do something dangerous.

12
00:00:46,840 --> 00:00:49,420
 And so the rogue server doesn't need to know the cookie.

13
00:00:49,420 --> 00:00:57,280
 The rogue server just needs to convince you to click on a rogue form to send to the request server.

14
00:00:57,280 --> 00:01:03,720
 So the defense for CSRF is to, don't be confused with session.

15
00:01:03,720 --> 00:01:05,300
 It is going to use session.

16
00:01:05,300 --> 00:01:08,260
 We're going to grab another large random number,

17
00:01:08,260 --> 00:01:12,460
 and we're going to call it the CSRF token, and we're going to stick that in the session.

18
00:01:12,460 --> 00:01:16,740
 And then what we do is every time we send a form out that's coming from our server,

19
00:01:16,740 --> 00:01:20,700
 we add a little input hidden tag that has this CSRF token.

20
00:01:20,700 --> 00:01:25,780
 And then when the post comes in, we check the CSRF token that's coming in and the post data,

21
00:01:25,780 --> 00:01:28,240
 and then we check it against the one that's in the session,

22
00:01:28,240 --> 00:01:30,260
 and then rejects it if it doesn't match.

23
00:01:30,260 --> 00:01:33,620
 So here's a picture of how this works, right?

24
00:01:33,620 --> 00:01:36,420
 So we'll have a legitimate server, right?

25
00:01:36,420 --> 00:01:38,960
 We're going to produce a page by the legitimate server,

26
00:01:38,960 --> 00:01:42,140
 and it's going to post back to this same server.

27
00:01:42,140 --> 00:01:45,700
 The action is the URL to send the post data to,

28
00:01:45,700 --> 00:01:49,740
 and we got some key value pairs and a submit button, right?

29
00:01:49,740 --> 00:01:52,900
 So you hit the submit button, and it's going to come back to the server.

30
00:01:52,900 --> 00:01:57,620
 Now, one of the things that the browser is supposed to do is pull the cookies

31
00:01:57,620 --> 00:01:59,420
 for that server and send it.

32
00:01:59,420 --> 00:02:02,380
 So it sends it both a post and the data,

33
00:02:02,380 --> 00:02:05,460
 but it also sends the session ID cookie.

34
00:02:05,460 --> 00:02:09,860
 And then what happens is is that the Django gets its hands on it,

35
00:02:09,860 --> 00:02:12,220
 it looks up the session ID, pulls it in,

36
00:02:12,220 --> 00:02:16,140
 and notices that it's CSEV and I've been logged as an instructor,

37
00:02:16,140 --> 00:02:21,820
 and then I can actually change this grade and set the grade, and it works.

38
00:02:21,820 --> 00:02:28,700
 Okay, now, here is what happens when you get to a CSRF attack.

39
00:02:28,700 --> 00:02:34,700
 So somehow a page gets sent to the server, right, sent from a rogue server,

40
00:02:34,700 --> 00:02:38,780
 and it just has this form, method equals post, action equals DJ.

41
00:02:38,780 --> 00:02:41,860
 It's not the action, it's going to a different place.

42
00:02:41,860 --> 00:02:45,660
 And it puts sort of a new grade and then a submit.

43
00:02:45,660 --> 00:02:49,340
 So what happens is is this submit comes in,

44
00:02:49,340 --> 00:02:54,420
 and the browser dutifully appends the cookie to it, and it sends it.

45
00:02:54,420 --> 00:02:57,540
 Now, you had to be tricked into getting to this page and

46
00:02:57,540 --> 00:02:59,860
 sometimes tricked into submitting the page.

47
00:02:59,860 --> 00:03:03,180
 But once the post comes in, it has legit cookie in it.

48
00:03:03,180 --> 00:03:06,580
 The cookie is used to look up the session and re-associate it.

49
00:03:06,580 --> 00:03:10,500
 And we can check in the session that the user is indeed logged in, and

50
00:03:10,500 --> 00:03:13,420
 we'll let the thing set the grade to 1.0.

51
00:03:13,420 --> 00:03:17,500
 So this would be a way if you could convince a logged in instructor

52
00:03:17,500 --> 00:03:23,220
 to run a post form that you created, you could basically change your grades.

53
00:03:23,220 --> 00:03:24,620
 So that's how it works.

54
00:03:24,620 --> 00:03:26,560
 That's how a CSRF attack.

55
00:03:26,560 --> 00:03:28,740
 You have to be tricked twice first.

56
00:03:28,740 --> 00:03:31,140
 But there's ways in JavaScript to make it so

57
00:03:31,140 --> 00:03:33,420
 it's hardly noticeable that you get tricked.

58
00:03:33,420 --> 00:03:41,460
 So if you do this with CSRF, the legit server basically adds another value,

59
00:03:41,460 --> 00:03:44,700
 not the session ID, but another value in the session,

60
00:03:44,700 --> 00:03:47,260
 which is a large randomly chosen number.

61
00:03:47,260 --> 00:03:51,220
 And then when a page comes out, it's a legit page, and

62
00:03:51,220 --> 00:03:56,380
 it uses a type hidden variable and puts the CSRF value in.

63
00:03:56,380 --> 00:04:02,560
 Now you hit the submit button, and the CSRF is coming in as post data.

64
00:04:02,560 --> 00:04:05,460
 The regular data, the grade data is coming in, and

65
00:04:05,460 --> 00:04:08,820
 the browser dutifully appends the session.

66
00:04:08,820 --> 00:04:12,500
 And so then using the session cookie, it re-associates the session.

67
00:04:12,500 --> 00:04:17,940
 It says, yep, you're C7, you're the instructor, and the CSRF works.

68
00:04:17,940 --> 00:04:22,340
 CSRF matches, so let's go ahead and let you set the grade.

69
00:04:22,340 --> 00:04:23,180
 So we let them in.

70
00:04:23,180 --> 00:04:29,380
 With the attack blocked, because the rogue server can generate a page, but

71
00:04:29,380 --> 00:04:36,380
 it doesn't know what the CSRF is, so who knows what the CSRF is?

72
00:04:36,380 --> 00:04:40,500
 So it generates it, maybe it can put a CSRF, but it doesn't know it.

73
00:04:40,500 --> 00:04:43,940
 So then the post happens, and all the data gets gathered up, and so

74
00:04:43,940 --> 00:04:47,060
 it sends the CSRF, but it's not the right CSRF.

75
00:04:47,060 --> 00:04:51,780
 The session ID is sent in, and so the session is pulled in.

76
00:04:51,780 --> 00:04:55,660
 We know it's user C7, we know it's instructor, but we're gonna check to see

77
00:04:55,660 --> 00:04:59,260
 if the CSRF matches, and then it blows up.

78
00:04:59,260 --> 00:05:03,100
 And so then you just refuse the post, probably log the user out, and

79
00:05:03,100 --> 00:05:05,420
 then log some kind of a security error.

80
00:05:05,420 --> 00:05:10,580
 So the idea is, is by having this little CSRF number in the session,

81
00:05:10,580 --> 00:05:13,300
 we can then take care of that.

82
00:05:13,300 --> 00:05:19,340
 So like most things, Django comes out of the box with CSRF protection built in.

83
00:05:19,340 --> 00:05:24,300
 Just like the session, we've got CSRF middleware just dropped in, and

84
00:05:24,300 --> 00:05:27,900
 actually it works automatically, you don't even have to ask for it to work.

85
00:05:27,900 --> 00:05:32,140
 Once you have a session, it starts putting out CSRF things.

86
00:05:32,140 --> 00:05:36,100
 So up next, we'll talk about, now that we know the concept of CSRF,

87
00:05:36,100 --> 00:05:40,340
 we'll talk about how we're going to use CSRF inside of forms to implement

88
00:05:40,340 --> 00:05:42,020
 sort of CSRF protection.

89
00:05:42,020 --> 00:05:52,020
 [MUSIC]

